('4cbc738b-a634-4236-bb2a-05d80a030849', 'Tailspin', '<p>\r\n	Ever wanted to grow up to be a spy? Do spy satellites and sting operations excite you? Do you think air surveillance is cool?</p>\r\n<p>\r\n	If yes, then you&rsquo;re just at the right coordinates.</p>\r\n<p>\r\n	Intense competition, soaring enthusiasm, a giant crowd and technological marvels of the 21st century competing neck and neck to be the best, just briefly describe Tailspin - a competition between radio controlled aircrafts trying to do their best in an innovative challenge: a challenge where it&rsquo;s not raw speed, power or agility that matters, but the genius of the designer and the brilliance of the flyer. Most aero modelling competitions are based on how fast the aircraft can go or how well it can manoeuvre.</p>\r\n<p>\r\n	Tailspin&nbsp;tests exactly these vital but ignored aspects by giving the participants payloads to fly with and having them perform air surveillance.</p>\r\n<p>\r\n	&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>\r\n	<u><strong>Prizes worth INR 25,000 to be won.</strong></u></p>\r\n', '<p>\r\n	<strong>Problem Statement</strong></p>\r\n<p>\r\n	&nbsp;&nbsp;Design and fly a wireless remote controlled aircraft capable of</p>\r\n<p>\r\n	&#9702; Flying around a ground with a given payload</p>\r\n<p>\r\n	&#9702; Landing as close as possible to a particular reference point</p>\r\n<p>\r\n	&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>\r\n	<strong>Arena Specifications</strong></p>\r\n<p>\r\n	1. Path: A circle of radius 50m</p>\r\n<p>\r\n	2. Landing zone: A circle of radius 7m</p>\r\n<p>\r\n	&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>\r\n	<strong>Machine Specifications</strong></p>\r\n<p>\r\n	1. An aircraft is defined as an object that has the four forces of flight, namely lift, drag, weight (gravity) and thrust due to propeller acting on it at any point of time.</p>\r\n<p>\r\n	2. The potential difference, between any two points on the machine, must be lower than or equal to 12V (recommended voltages 7.2V, 7.4V, 8.4V, 9.6V, 11.4V or 12V) at any point of time during the competition.</p>\r\n<p>\r\n	3. The use of launching mechanisms is prohibited.</p>\r\n<p>\r\n	4. The use of IC engines is prohibited. Only electrical motors are allowed.</p>\r\n<p>\r\n	5. The weight of aircraft should not exceed &nbsp;700 gm. Points will be deducted for aircrafts weighing above this limit depending on the excess mass.</p>\r\n<p>\r\n	6. Participants must make all parts of the aircraft themselves. Usage of Ready-to-Fly (RTF) and Almost-Ready-to-Fly (ARF) kits is strictly prohibited. However, kits comprising of unassembled cut-pieces of Balsa wood are allowed. Use of readymade actuators/motors, remote controls and propellers is also allowed.</p>\r\n<p>\r\n	7. Anyone found not following the above rules is subject to disqualification.</p>\r\n<p>\r\n	&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>\r\n	<strong>Event Specifications</strong></p>\r\n<p>\r\n	<strong>Abstract &nbsp;Submission</strong>: All the write-ups will be used strictly for the elimination purpose. The Quark policy ensures that no information will be made available to any third party. Please pay adequate attention to the write-up. It is meant to assess the efforts put in by participants and their capability in design and fabrication. Each team will have to send us few pictures of their model.</p>\r\n<p>\r\n	&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>\r\n	<strong>Round 1</strong>: In this round we will be checking whether your aircraft is compatible with all the machine specifications mentioned above.</p>\r\n<p>\r\n	&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>\r\n	<strong>Round 2: </strong>In this round the teams start off with the problem statement. It is subdivided into 2 runs. Each run will comprise of 3 trials.</p>\r\n<p>\r\n	&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>\r\n	1. <strong>Run 1</strong>: The team will have an option between two given payloads(100gms and 200gms). They are required to do two rounds of the path in minimum time with the chosen payload and land safely.</p>\r\n<p>\r\n	&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>\r\n	2. <strong>Run 2</strong>: Top 10 scorers from Run 1 will qualify for Run 2. There will be 3 bags kept at different places on the ground. A camera recording a video will be securely attached to the aircraft and the team will have to fly over the three bags such that an image of each bag is recorded in the video.</p>\r\n', 'tailspin', '4af9dd07-f94c-42fb-ad6d-1064bb1aea99', '<p>\r\n	<strong>General Rules</strong></p>\r\n<p>\r\n	1.The teams must adhere to the spirit of healthy competition. The teams must not damage an opponent&#39;s aircraft in any way. Judges reserve the right to disqualify any team indulging in misbehaviour.</p>\r\n<p>\r\n	2.Any team that is not ready at the time specified will be disqualified from the competition.</p>\r\n<p>\r\n	3.The aircraft would be checked for its safe operation before the event and would be discarded if found unsafe for other participants or spectators.</p>\r\n<p>\r\n	4.The organizers reserve all rights to change any or all of the above rules as they deem fit. Change in any rule, if any, will be highlighted on the website.</p>\r\n<p>\r\n	5.The wind conditions are uncontrollable by the coordinators, so any complaints of unfair advantage/disadvantage will not be entertained.</p>\r\n<p>\r\n	6.The transmitters of all the teams will be safely secured by the coordinators during the event to prevent frequency clashes.</p>\r\n<p>\r\n	7.You are expected to bring your own battery chargers.</p>\r\n<p>\r\n	8.The thrust source has to be electrical motors. Any other means of propulsion is not allowed.</p>\r\n<p>\r\n	9. Electric sockets will be provided in the stadium for battery chargers. These would be standard AC mains. You are expected to bring all the supporting equipment for your glider. No complaints will be entertained in this regard</p>\r\n', '<p>\r\n	&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>\r\n	<strong>&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; Judging Criteria</strong></p>\r\n<p>\r\n	<strong>Landing Points </strong>(LP):</p>\r\n<p>\r\n	Distance from centre of landing zone &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;Points</p>\r\n<p>\r\n	&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>\r\n	Less than 1m &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;100</p>\r\n<p>\r\n	1m to 3m &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp; 80</p>\r\n<p>\r\n	3m to 5m &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp; 60</p>\r\n<p>\r\n	5m to 7m &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp; 40</p>\r\n<p>\r\n	Safe landing outside landing zone &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; 10</p>\r\n<p>\r\n	Crash landing &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; 0</p>\r\n<p>\r\n	&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>\r\n	<strong>&nbsp;&nbsp;Run 1:</strong></p>\r\n<p>\r\n	Time Points (TP) = 300-T &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;(T is the time taken to complete the task in seconds)</p>\r\n<p>\r\n	2. &nbsp;Payload Points (PP) = W/4 &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;(W is the weight of the payload in grams)</p>\r\n<p>\r\n	&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>\r\n	<strong>&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; TOTAL = TP + WP + LP</strong></p>\r\n<p>\r\n	&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>\r\n	<strong>&nbsp;Run 2:</strong></p>\r\n<p>\r\n	Time Points (TP) = 240-T &nbsp;(T is the time taken to complete the task in seconds)</p>\r\n<p>\r\n	&nbsp;Video Points (VP) = N*25 &nbsp;&nbsp;(N is the number of bags covered in the video)</p>\r\n<p>\r\n	&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>\r\n	<strong>&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;TOTAL = TP + VP + LP</strong></p>\r\n<p>\r\n	&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>\r\n	<strong>Note</strong>: Points from Run 1 will NOT be carried onto Run 2.</p>\r\n', '', '<p>\r\n	If you have any query, please send an e-mail to <strong><br />\r\n	tailspin@bits-quark.org</strong> or get in touch with any one of us:<br />\r\n	&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>\r\n	<strong>AsheshKaushik <br />\r\n	</strong>+91 9503817733</p>\r\n<p>\r\n	<strong><span class="Apple-style-span" style="color: rgb(136, 136, 136); font-family: arial, sans-serif; font-weight: normal; font-size: 13px; border-collapse: collapse; ">Kriti Garuda</span></strong><br />\r\n	<span class="Apple-style-span" style="color: rgb(136, 136, 136); font-family: arial, sans-serif; font-size: 13px; border-collapse: collapse; "><strong>963742354</strong>4</span></p>\r\n', 1, 5),
('4cbc741c-6c44-47d5-a18e-05d80a030849', 'Chem-Buzz ', '<p>\r\n	Does your mind hover around the mingling molecules, the popping of a bubble and the odour of a distinctive ammonia leak? If yes, then gather your vague thoughts to perform untested&nbsp;experiments and portray them to work out the real life problems in your own way .Get ready for the challenge!!</p>\r\n<p>\r\n	&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>\r\n	<u><strong>Prizes worth INR 8,000 to be won.</strong></u></p>\r\n', '<p>\r\n	<span style="font-size: 14px;"><strong>Round Descriptions:</strong><br />\r\n	</span></p>\r\n<p>\r\n	<br />\r\n	<strong>Elimination Round: </strong></p>\r\n<p>\r\n	It will consist of a written MCQ based on the latest advancements and practical applications of various fields of Chemistry. Some questions might be based on basic understanding of the subject. No mugged up reactions or dreadful organic structures to worry about!&nbsp; There will be equal weightage for all questions and negative marking for wrong responses, along with a few tie-breaker questions.</p>\r\n<p>\r\n	<strong>Rapid Fire Round:</strong></p>\r\n<p>\r\n	&bull;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Each team will be asked short questions with a time limit of 2 minutes. The more questions you answer correctly, the more points you get. <br />\r\n	&bull;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; The participants will be shown some clips related to general chemistry, based on which, questions will be asked.</p>\r\n<p>\r\n	<strong>Final Round:</strong></p>\r\n<p>\r\n	The participants are expected to make use of the information provided and implement that with their pre-existing basic knowledge of reactions to make the best possible combination out of several possible. The effect specified will have a definite quantitative measurability to provide for the judging criterion in the given time period.<br />\r\n	&nbsp;</p>\r\n', 'chembuzz', '4af9dd68-4c24-4a0b-b772-1064bb1aea99', '<ul>\r\n	<li>\r\n		Time duration &ndash;</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p>\r\n	&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp; Elimination round: 60 minutes<br />\r\n	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Rapid Fire Round: 45 minutes.<br />\r\n	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Final round: 90 minutes</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>\r\n		10 teams will be selected for the final round, on the basis of the elimination round.</li>\r\n	<li>\r\n		Rapid&nbsp; fire round will be subdivided into two rounds as follows:<br />\r\n		<br />\r\n		i.&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;Each team will be given 2 minutes to answer as many questions as it can in this given time constraint.There is no negative marking for any wrong answer and passing of questions to other teams is not permitted in this round.<br />\r\n		<br />\r\n		ii.&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;A total of 5 questions will be asked based on 5 different video clips which will be shown to the teams. For each question asked, the team that answers the question correctly in the minimum time will be awarded points .However, if answered incorrectly, the question will be passed on to the team that answers the same question in the next minimum time.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>\r\n		Fixed and equal amounts of chemicals will be provided to all the teams in the final round.</li>\r\n	<li>\r\n		In final round number of trials fixed for each team - a maximum of 3.</li>\r\n	<li>\r\n		Final score of each team will be determined from the best of 3&nbsp; trials.</li>\r\n	<li>\r\n		For the final round the score will be directly derived by comparing the measure of the physical/chemical effect(s) produced to the desired effect(s).</li>\r\n	<li>\r\n		The final score of each team will be derived from the cumulative score of the Rapid Fire Round and the Final Round.</li>\r\n	<li>\r\n		In case of a tie, the effectiveness of the models will be compared by the event judge, and winner will be decided accordingly. <br />\r\n		&nbsp;</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n', '', '', '<p>\r\n	If you have any query, please send an e-mail to <strong>chembuzz@bits-quark.org</strong> or get in touch with any one of us:<br />\r\n	<br />\r\n	<strong>Mani Awasthi</strong><br />\r\n	+91 9049512912<br />\r\n	<br />\r\n	<strong>Pallavi Muktesh</strong><br />\r\n	+91 9049080917</p>\r\n', 2, 3),
('4cbc74a8-4340-4ac0-bb0c-05d80a030849', 'Dexter''s Lab', '<p>\r\n	Come showcase your creativity in QUARK 2011. All you need is common sense, quick judgment and an idea to make it big in this event. There are no pre-requisites for this three-round event. Grab the opportunity to explore your creative engineering instincts by participating in Dexter&#39;s Lab.</p>\r\n<p>\r\n	&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>\r\n	<u><strong>Prizes worth INR 8,000 to be won.</strong></u></p>\r\n', '<p>\r\n	It is basically an event where we focus on the application skills of the participants. They will have to experimentally demonstrate any of the physical laws given to them using junk. It is designed to test how creative and innovative the participants can get.</p>\r\n<h2>\r\n	Round Description :</h2>\r\n<p>\r\n	The event comprises of three rounds. The description of all the three rounds is as follows.</p>\r\n<p>\r\n	<strong>Round 1:</strong></p>\r\n<p>\r\n	This round is basically to test the application skills of the participants by giving them a questionnaire of 5-6 questions to be solved over a period of 1 hour. The questions will be related to everyday phenomena and elementary knowledge (+2 level) of science will be sufficient. This will be conducted on Day 2 of QUARK.</p>\r\n<p>\r\n	&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>\r\n	<strong>Round 3 :</strong></p>\r\n<p>\r\n	This is the final round and tests the innovativeness and creativity of the participants. In this round, the participants will be provided with some junk (cardboard, straw, wood, bottles etc) which will be common to all. They will also be given a list of basic and general laws of science. For example:</p>\r\n<p>\r\n	&middot; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; Law of conservation of momentum</p>\r\n<p>\r\n	&middot; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; Law of conservation of energy</p>\r\n<p>\r\n	&middot; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; Archimedes&rsquo; Principle</p>\r\n<p>\r\n	&middot; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; Newton&rsquo;s Laws of motion</p>\r\n<p>\r\n	&middot; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; Static Electricity</p>\r\n<p>\r\n	&middot; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; Optical Illusions</p>\r\n<p>\r\n	&middot; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; Laws of reflection\\refraction.</p>\r\n<p>\r\n	&middot; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; Existence of Centre of mass\\gravity.</p>\r\n<p>\r\n	&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>\r\n	The participants are allowed to pick any one of the above mentioned laws and with the material provided, they have to make a model and experimentally demonstrate the particular law chosen. Marks will be awarded on the basis of their innovativeness, creativity, how well have they explained the law, how efficiently their model works and other miscellaneous criteria. They will be given 3 hours to make their models.</p>\r\n<p>\r\n	&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>\r\n	<strong>Tie Breaker:</strong></p>\r\n<p>\r\n	In case two teams have same total score, higher preference will be given to the team having higher score in the 3rd round. Suppose the 3rd round scores are the same then next preference will be given to the 2nd round scores and last preference will be given to the 1st round scores, i.e., amongst teams having same final total score, the team with a higher 3rd round score wins.</p>\r\n<p>\r\n	&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>\r\n	<strong>Selection Process :</strong></p>\r\n<p>\r\n	* &nbsp;Top 20 teams from the 1st round will qualify for the second round.</p>\r\n<p>\r\n	* &nbsp;Top 10 teams from the 2nd round will qualify for the 3rd round.</p>\r\n<p>\r\n	* &nbsp;Final top 3 teams will share the prizes.</p>\r\n', 'dexter', '4af9dd68-4c24-4a0b-b772-1064bb1aea99', '<p>\r\n	<strong>Round 1</strong></p>\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>\r\n		Maximum time to answer the given set of questions should not exceed 60 min</li>\r\n	<li>\r\n		No electronic gadgets allowed</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p>\r\n	<strong>Round 3</strong></p>\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>\r\n		Maximum time for making the model must not exceed 3 hrs</li>\r\n	<li>\r\n		No other stuff can be used except the provided junk. In case of extreme need where a team wants to use something they have to enhance their model or make it work. They can do so with the permission of event managers but they are then liable to lose points for every new thing they use. The decision of how many points are to be deducted will lie solely in the hands of the judges and their decision would be final. No claims whatsoever would be entertained thereafter.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n', '', '', '<p>\r\n	If you have any query, please send an e-mail to <strong>dexterslab@bits-quark.org</strong> or get in touch with any one of us:<br />\r\n	<br />\r\n	<strong>Ranjita Pai Kasturi</strong><br />\r\n	+91 9561431298<br />\r\n	<br />\r\n	<strong>Rachit Kulshreshtha</strong><br />\r\n	+91 9673712939</p>\r\n', 2, 3),
('4cbc74e2-558c-47cb-8f96-05d80a030849', 'Numb3rs 2.0', '<p>\r\n	Ever wondered how terrorist activity is monitored by defence ministries, and how they find out about the place and time of danger?<br />\r\n	<br />\r\n	NUMB3RS is an event that will bring out the mathematician within us all. It is interesting to see how playing with patterns and series of numbers can help us solve notorious cases. In this event, participants selected from a written quiz in the first round, will be teamed up and presented with a complete case study, to be solved by observing and manipulating some nerve-wracking numeric codes</p>\r\n<p>\r\n	&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>\r\n	<u><strong>Prizes worth INR 8,000 to be won.</strong></u></p>\r\n', '<p>\r\n	<strong>Event Specifications:</strong><br />\r\n	<br />\r\n	No. of rounds: 3<br />\r\n	&nbsp; <br />\r\n	<span style="text-decoration: underline;"><span style="font-weight: bold;">Round Description</span></span><br />\r\n	<br />\r\n	<strong>Round 1</strong><br />\r\n	<br />\r\n	Elimination Round:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>\r\n		&nbsp;This round will be of 60min duration</li>\r\n	<li>\r\n		&nbsp;It will consist of objective as well as subjective questions</li>\r\n	<li>\r\n		&nbsp;20 teams will be selected from this round</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p>\r\n	<strong>Round 2</strong><br />\r\n	<br />\r\n	Rapid Fire Round:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>\r\n		Bonus question round</li>\r\n	<li>\r\n		Questions will be projected on the screen</li>\r\n	<li>\r\n		Teams will answer by pressing buzzers.</li>\r\n	<li>\r\n		Questions will be objective.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p>\r\n	<strong>Round 3</strong><br />\r\n	<br />\r\n	Final Round:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>\r\n		&nbsp;All the clues will have equal weightage.</li>\r\n	<li>\r\n		&nbsp;Participants who ask for hints for a specific clue will have some percentage of the marks for that clue deducted according to the number of hints asked.</li>\r\n	<li>\r\n		The team that solves the case the fastest wins</li>\r\n	<li>\r\n		&nbsp;If none are able to solve the case completely, the team with maximum marks will win.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p>\r\n	<br />\r\n	<strong>Tie- breaker</strong><br />\r\n	<br />\r\n	In the final round, the team with the maximum points would win. In case of a tie of the scores, the team that took less time to solve the case wins.<br />\r\n	<br />\r\n	<strong>&nbsp;<br />\r\n	Selection Process</strong></p>\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li>\r\n		Top 20 teams from round 1 will go to next round</li>\r\n	<li>\r\n		All the teams of round 2 will go to next round, but three will get bonus points.</li>\r\n	<li>\r\n		Out of 20 in the final round, the first three will be rewarded.<br />\r\n		&nbsp;</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n', 'numbers', '4af9dd68-4c24-4a0b-b772-1064bb1aea99', '<p>\r\n	<strong>Round 1</strong></p>\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>\r\n		&nbsp;No points will be carried over</li>\r\n	<li>\r\n		Since the 1st round is based on reasoning and innovation, answers should be supported by proper reasoning</li>\r\n	<li>\r\n		Any kind of electronic gadget is not allowed</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p>\r\n	<strong>Round 2</strong></p>\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>\r\n		Wrong answer will lead to negative marking</li>\r\n	<li>\r\n		First three teams will get bonus points for the final round</li>\r\n	<li>\r\n		5 seconds will be given to answer the question and no answer will be counted as a wrong answer</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p>\r\n	<strong>Round 3</strong></p>\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>\r\n		It will be announced on the spot</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n', '', '', '<p>\r\n	If you have any query, please send an e-mail to <strong>numb3rs@bits-quark.org</strong> or get in touch with any one of us:</p>\r\n<p>\r\n	<strong>Nehil Jain<br />\r\n	</strong>+91 9049268862&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>\r\n	&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>\r\n	<strong>Abhay Raj&nbsp;<br />\r\n	</strong>+91 9096214082</p>\r\n', 1, 3),
('4cbc759d-38ec-46d0-b635-05d80a030849', 'Catch me if you can', '<p>\r\n	Officer: &ldquo;Robocop come in!! Over. Robocop come in!! Over &hellip;.&rdquo;<br />\r\n	<br />\r\n	Robocop: &ldquo;Robocop at your service! What&rsquo;s the situation officer?!...Over!&rdquo;<br />\r\n	<br />\r\n	Officer: &ldquo;There&rsquo;s been a bank robbery in the town. The elements behind this crime are none other than the famous trio Mr. Circle, Mr. Star and Mr. Square. The criminals are absconding with a huge sum of money worth millions of rupees. All three members of the gang have out driven us and will soon be out of reach .Now it&rsquo;s up to you to catch them before they cross the borders of this town and bring them to justice! But beware, the three thieves are well known for their haphazard behaviour... Over!&rdquo;<br />\r\n	<br />\r\n	Robocop: &ldquo;Roger that! Over and Out!&rdquo;<br />\r\n	<br />\r\n	//--------<strong>Welcome to the image processing section of robotics</strong>--------//</p>\r\n<p>\r\n	&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>\r\n	<u><strong>Prizes worth INR 15,000 to be won.</strong></u></p>\r\n', '<p>\r\n	&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>\r\n	<strong>Problem statement<br />\r\n	</strong></p>\r\n<p>\r\n	Make a computer controlled bot which can recognize the standard square, star and circle patterns in motion and stop them by getting close to the bots within a radius of 10 cm from the center of any bot,(this will be checked by our image processing code and a readout will be available on the projector), with the help of an <strong>over head camera</strong>.</p>\r\n<p>\r\n	<strong>Arena Specifications</strong></p>\r\n<p>\r\n	1.<span class="Apple-tab-span" style="white-space:pre"> </span>The arena is a plane white surface of dimension 200cm X 200cm.</p>\r\n<p>\r\n	2.<span class="Apple-tab-span" style="white-space:pre"> </span>The arena is surrounded by a black border of thickness 5cm.</p>\r\n<p>\r\n	<strong>Pattern Specifications</strong></p>\r\n<p>\r\n	1)<span class="Apple-tab-span" style="white-space:pre"> </span>Each of the patterns square, circle and star are mounted on three different criminal bots which move autonomously in the arena.</p>\r\n<p>\r\n	2)<span class="Apple-tab-span" style="white-space:pre"> </span>The size of the criminal bots is 12cm X 12cm X 15cm.</p>\r\n<p>\r\n	3)<span class="Apple-tab-span" style="white-space:pre"> </span>Size of the plane surface on which each pattern is made is 12cm X 12cm.(including LEDs)</p>\r\n<p>\r\n	4)<span class="Apple-tab-span" style="white-space:pre"> </span>Following are the dimensions of each of the patterns:</p>\r\n<p>\r\n	a.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Square: 8cm X 8cm.</p>\r\n<p>\r\n	b.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Circle: Radius=5cm.</p>\r\n<p>\r\n	c.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Star(6-point Hexagram): Distance b/w opposite vertices = 5&radic;3.</p>\r\n<p>\r\n	5) &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;Color of all the patterns is black</p>\r\n<p>\r\n	6)<span class="Apple-tab-span" style="white-space:pre"> </span>The top right corner of each pattern will have 4 red LEDs in a 2X2 square. These will &nbsp;switched on for 10 seconds when the bot has been immobilized and this will serve as an indicator to the participant bot to move on</p>\r\n<p>\r\n	Arena</p>\r\n<p>\r\n	&nbsp;<img alt="" height="282" src="http://www.bits-quark.org/portal/img/uploads/catch2.PNG" style="height: 282px; width: 424px; " width="424" /></p>\r\n<p>\r\n	&nbsp;Square pattern</p>\r\n<p>\r\n	<img alt="" height="224" src="http://www.bits-quark.org/portal/img/uploads/square2copy.jpg" width="424" /></p>\r\n<p>\r\n	Circle pattern</p>\r\n<p>\r\n	<img alt="" height="389" src="http://www.bits-quark.org/portal/img/uploads/circle1copy.jpg" style="height: 389px; width: 424px; " width="424" /></p>\r\n<p>\r\n	Star pattern</p>\r\n<p>\r\n	<img alt="" height="222" src="http://www.bits-quark.org/portal/img/uploads/star2copy.jpg" style="height: 222px; width: 424px; " width="424" /></p>\r\n', 'cmiuc', '4af9dd54-68fc-4cdf-b8da-1064bb1aea99', '<p>\r\n	&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>\r\n	<strong>Bot specification</strong></p>\r\n<p>\r\n	1.<span class="Apple-tab-span" style="white-space:pre"> </span>Each team is allowed to have only one bot.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>\r\n	2.<span class="Apple-tab-span" style="white-space:pre"> </span>The bot must fit into a cube of 20 cm x 20 cm x 20 cm at all times. It may not expand at any point during it&#39;s run beyond these dimensions. Violating this will lead to immediate disqualification.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>\r\n	3.<span class="Apple-tab-span" style="white-space:pre"> </span>The bot has to use an onboard power supply. No external power supply will be allowed. The max potential difference between any two points should not exceed 24 V. Only electrical propulsion is allowed, no form of chemical propulsion or ic engines can be used.</p>\r\n<p>\r\n	4.<span class="Apple-tab-span" style="white-space:pre"> </span>The robotic equipment is to be fully autonomous. Human operators are not permitted to enter any information into the equipment during a run. The human operator should not directly control the motion of their robots with a joystick or by keyboard commands under any circumstances.</p>\r\n<p>\r\n	5.<span class="Apple-tab-span" style="white-space:pre"> </span>All the bots have to work on the principle of image processing. Any sort of ambiguity will lead to immediate disqualification. In case of doubt please confirm with the organizers about the validity of your procedure beforehand, via email</p>\r\n<p>\r\n	6.<span class="Apple-tab-span" style="white-space:pre"> </span>The bot must be fully independent, with powering and motoring mechanisms self contained. However, it can communicate with the computer using either wireless data transfer.</p>\r\n<p>\r\n	<strong>Wireless data transfer</strong></p>\r\n<p>\r\n	&bull;<span class="Apple-tab-span" style="white-space:pre"> </span>The bot can only use rf transmitters and receivers. They can be &nbsp;modules that work at 433 MHz , 315 MHz or 2.4 GHz modules that must have the ability to change channels so as to not interfere with organizers transmission.</p>\r\n<p>\r\n	&bull;<span class="Apple-tab-span" style="white-space:pre"> </span>These modules (both the transmitter and receiver) have to be removable, so that they can be submitted to the organizers during another bots final run.</p>\r\n<p>\r\n	&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>\r\n	<strong>&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;7. &nbsp;Tag to identify bot:</strong></p>\r\n<p>\r\n	&nbsp;&nbsp;The tag to identify the bot (in the image processing) is fixed and will be provided by the &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;organizers (this is so because the organizers need to track the bot). The specifications of the &nbsp; tag are as follows.</p>\r\n<p>\r\n	&bull;<span class="Apple-tab-span" style="white-space:pre"> </span>The tag will be of size 20cm X 20cm.</p>\r\n<p>\r\n	&bull;<span class="Apple-tab-span" style="white-space:pre"> </span>The <strong>front side</strong> 10cm X 20cm will be blue (fluorescent paper) The<strong> rear side </strong>10cm X 20cm will be bright green (fluorescent paper)</p>\r\n<p>\r\n	(Approximate RGB values will be provided beforehand, accurate values will be provided on the day of the event)</p>\r\n<p>\r\n	For this purpose, the teams are required to provide a flat horizontal surface of size at least 10cm X 10cm on top of their bot to attach the tag by DST. The teams can use their own tags for practice. Spare tags will be provided for calibration.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<div>\r\n	<b><br />\r\n	</b></div>\r\n<p>\r\n	&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>\r\n	<strong>Setup</strong></p>\r\n<p>\r\n	Competition setup consists of a plane arena white in color. All the patterns (circle, square, star) will be of same color black. The patterns (battery powered) move randomly in the arena. There would be one overhead camera perpendicular to the ramp. Its mandatory for all teams to use the same camera. Apart from this we also provide a desktop computer with a color monitor, mouse and keyboard preinstalled with <strong>windows 7</strong>, <strong>Matlab 2009</strong> and <strong>Open cv</strong>. Participants are although advised to bring their own Laptops (<strong>Desktop PCs are not allowed</strong>) which can be connected to this system . All the participants also have to get there codes in a virus free pen drive. The drivers for the webcam will be provided on the day of the event.</p>\r\n<p>\r\n	<b><br />\r\n	</b></p>\r\n<p>\r\n	<b>CAMERA &nbsp; &nbsp; : &nbsp;LOGITECH&nbsp;</b></p>\r\n<p>\r\n	<b>MODEL NO : &nbsp;V-UBQ42</b></p>\r\n<p>\r\n	&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>\r\n	<img alt="" height="221" src="http://www.bits-quark.org/portal/img/uploads/cameralogitech.JPG" width="424" /></p>\r\n<p>\r\n	<b><br />\r\n	</b></p>\r\n<p>\r\n	<strong>Calibration</strong></p>\r\n<p>\r\n	Each team will be given 15 minutes to calibrate their bot to the arena settings. Participants can also make a test run during this time. No extra time will be given for calibration afterwards.</p>\r\n<p>\r\n	&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>\r\n	<strong>Calibration</strong></p>\r\n<p>\r\n	Each team will be given 15 minutes to calibrate their bot to the arena settings. Participants can also make a test run during this time. &nbsp;No extra time will be given for calibration afterwards.</p>\r\n<p>\r\n	<strong>Gameplay&nbsp;</strong></p>\r\n<p>\r\n	The competition is a single run game where only 1 team can participate at a time. Before starting of round the participant&rsquo;s bot is placed in the center of arena. Only 3 minutes will be provided before each round for the participants to set up. &nbsp;Initial position of the patterns may vary from team to team. For each round maximum of 3min is allowed. Particular round will be disqualified if the bot jumps out of the arena.</p>\r\n<p>\r\n	The organizer will have a separate webcam and computer, the output of which will be shown on a Projection screen. A circle of radius 10cm will be drawn from the center of each of each of the patterns(not in reality but by the organizers code and will be shown on screen to silence any disparities). The participant bot has to come within this circle to immobilize the bot, the organizers code will track this. As soon as the participant bot enters this zone, the bot will stop and 4 bright red LEDs on the bot wilol glow for a duration of 10 seconds. Participants can use these lights to indicate that the bot has stopped and mve on to the next one.</p>\r\n<p>\r\n	<strong>Rounds</strong></p>\r\n<p>\r\n	&nbsp;The competition is divided in to three &nbsp;rounds</p>\r\n<p>\r\n	1)<span class="Apple-tab-span" style="white-space:pre"> </span>Judge inspection and practice</p>\r\n<p>\r\n	2)<span class="Apple-tab-span" style="white-space:pre"> </span>Round 1 ( Qualifying Round )</p>\r\n<p>\r\n	3)<span class="Apple-tab-span" style="white-space:pre"> </span>Round 2 ( Final Round )</p>\r\n<p>\r\n	<strong>Judge Inspection And Practice</strong></p>\r\n<p>\r\n	This include the fifteen minutes of calibration &nbsp;and submission of codes &nbsp;to judges.Validity of the bot is also checked in this round</p>\r\n<p>\r\n	<strong>Round 1</strong></p>\r\n<p>\r\n	In this round the participants have to stop 3 patterns (any order) which will be randomly moving in the arena with different speeds.</p>\r\n<p>\r\n	1.<span class="Apple-tab-span" style="white-space:pre"> </span>circle: static</p>\r\n<p>\r\n	2.<span class="Apple-tab-span" style="white-space:pre"> </span>square: half of max speed (max speed is the speed of &nbsp;bot in final round )</p>\r\n<p>\r\n	3.<span class="Apple-tab-span" style="white-space:pre"> </span>star: at the max speed&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>\r\n	Depending on score top 7 teams will be selected</p>\r\n<p>\r\n	<strong>Round 2</strong></p>\r\n<p>\r\n	In this round each team will be given a particular order in which the patterns are to be stopped. Maximum of 3 min will be given for each team.</p>\r\n<p>\r\n	Final winner will be decided based on the points</p>\r\n<div>\r\n	<b><br />\r\n	</b></div>\r\n', '<p>\r\n	&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>\r\n	<strong>Scoring</strong></p>\r\n<p>\r\n	<strong><br />\r\n	</strong></p>\r\n<p>\r\n	<strong>Scoring for round 1</strong></p>\r\n<p>\r\n	Scoring formula</p>\r\n<p>\r\n	Round 1 score= (180-T)+ 10 A Circle + 20 A &nbsp;Square + 40 A Star</p>\r\n<p>\r\n	T = time in seconds in which all the balls are stopped (will be considered as 180 if bot failed to stop all 3)</p>\r\n<p>\r\n	A = 1 if the shape is stopped 0 if not.</p>\r\n<p>\r\n	&nbsp;Top 7 teams will go on to round 2 the teams which qualify the first round will then enter the round 2</p>\r\n<p>\r\n	&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>\r\n	<strong>Scoring for round 2</strong></p>\r\n<p>\r\n	Scoring formula</p>\r\n<p>\r\n	Final score = (180-T)+ 40*O + 30* S</p>\r\n<p>\r\n	T = time in seconds in which all the balls are stopped (will be considered as 180 if bot failed to stop all 3)</p>\r\n<p>\r\n	O = Correct order (0-3)</p>\r\n<p>\r\n	Example: suppose order is cylinder, square, star</p>\r\n<p>\r\n	O = 1 (if the bot selected in order cylinder, star, square)</p>\r\n<p>\r\n	O = 2 (if bot selected cylinder, star correct but failed to stop star)</p>\r\n<p>\r\n	O = 3 (for the correct order followed)</p>\r\n<p>\r\n	S= no of balls stopped (0-3)</p>\r\n<p>\r\n	Final winner will be the one with highest score. In case of tie Team with highest O will be ranked 1, even then it&rsquo;s a tie then Team which completed it in least time will be ranked 1. Incase teams have same O and T then both will be ranked 1</p>\r\n<p>\r\n	<br />\r\n	&nbsp;<br />\r\n	&nbsp;</p>\r\n', '<p>\r\n	&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>\r\n	<a href="http://www.bits-quark.org/portal/files/attachments-1.zip">The arena pics can be downloaded here</a></p>\r\n<p>\r\n	<strong>Resources</strong></p>\r\n<p>\r\n	<a href="http://www.mathworks.cn/matlabcentral/fileexchange/15491">http://www.mathworks.cn/matlabcentral/fileexchange/15491</a></p>\r\n<p>\r\n	<a href="http://www.pages.drexel.edu/~nk752/tutorials.html">http://www.pages.drexel.edu/~nk752/tutorials.html</a></p>\r\n<p>\r\n	<a href="http://www.mathworks.com/matlabcentral/fileexchange/20666-shape-recognitionmany-shape">http://www.mathworks.com/matlabcentral/fileexchange/20666-shape-recognitionmany-shape</a></p>\r\n<p>\r\n	<a href="http://madan.wordpress.com/2007/03/23/image-capture-using-webcam-in-matlab/">http://madan.wordpress.com/2007/03/23/image-capture-using-webcam-in-matlab/</a></p>\r\n', '<p>\r\n	If you have any query, please send an e-mail to <strong>catchme@bits-quark.org</strong>, or get in touch with any one of us:</p>\r\n<p>\r\n	<strong>Harshvardhan Reddy<br />\r\n	</strong>+917798607488</p>\r\n<p>\r\n	<strong>Abhinav Mehra<br />\r\n	</strong>+919765795145</p>\r\n', 0, 4);
INSERT INTO `events` (`id`, `name`, `intro`, `details`, `route`, `category_id`, `rules`, `judging_criteria`, `additional_info`, `contact`, `min_participants`, `max_participants`) VALUES
('4cbc75e8-7eb4-48d0-9b19-05d80a030849', 'City Maps', '<p>\r\n	Imagine that you are a pizza delivery man and you have a particular sector in your locality assigned to you. The pizza joint that you work for has this unique feature that it delivers the pizzas within 20 minutes after the customers have placed an order , given the sector that they stay in is the same as the that of the joint, failing which the pizza is given for free. And here&rsquo;s the problematic part, as the pizza delivery man it is your job to keep this promise. If you fail, you pay half the price of the pizza. So here&rsquo;s an opportunity to save yourself the money, and think of a way, such that you are always on time and are awarded the bonus for the &ldquo; Best Pizza Delivery Man&rdquo;&hellip;&hellip;&hellip;..</p>\r\n<p>\r\n	&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>\r\n	<u><strong>Prizes worth INR 20,000 to be won.</strong></u></p>\r\n', '<p>\r\n	<strong>Central Idea: </strong><br />\r\n	ROUND 1: To make a basic line follower that can traverse from the starting point to the finish point by necessarily using the bridge provided and stop at the penalty point for 5 seconds wherever it encounters them. <a href="http://www.bits-quark.org/portal/files/arenapics.rar">(see images for further understanding)&nbsp;</a>&nbsp;&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>\r\n	<br />\r\n	<img alt="" src="http://www.bits-quark.org/portal/img/uploads/arenaround1mod.PNG" style="width: 410px; height: 291px;" /><br />\r\n	ROUND 2: This round involves making a line following bot that starts at the starting point, traverses through a grid, and reaches the delivery point and also traverses back. This shortest path can be obtained using the dry run that will be given before the actual run takes place. The arena consists of penalty points at random nodes and bridges which can be used to shorten the time of traversing via a node and also skip a penalty point node in case the bridge is placed in that way. The dry run should be used to map the positions of penalty points and bridges in the arena.</p>\r\n<p>\r\n	<span class="Apple-style-span" style="color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: ''Courier New''; font-size: medium; border-collapse: collapse; ">NOTE:The positions of penalty points and bridges will be different in the actual arena although the grid structure shown below will remain same. The participant is expected to map the positions of penalty points and bridges in the dry run and use that information to find the most optimum path from the Starting Point to the Delivery Point and back.</span></p>\r\n<p>\r\n	<a href="http://www.bits-quark.org/portal/files/arenapics.rar">(see images for further understanding) </a></p>\r\n<p>\r\n	<img alt="" src="http://www.bits-quark.org/portal/img/uploads/arenaround2mod.PNG" style="width: 417px; height: 438px;" /></p>\r\n<p>\r\n	<br />\r\n	<strong>Path Description</strong>: The paths are 3 cm wide and the bridges are 1.5 cm wide.</p>\r\n<p>\r\n	<strong>Penalty point node description: </strong>The penalty points will be nodes with the color same as the background color of the arena (see figure).</p>\r\n<p>\r\n	<br />\r\n	<strong>Bot Specifications</strong>:<br />\r\n	1.&nbsp;The bot must fit into a cube of dimensions 20cm X 20 cm X 20cm.<br />\r\n	2.&nbsp;The maximum voltage difference between any 2 points on the bot must not exceed 12 volts.<br />\r\n	3.&nbsp;The bot should be fully autonomous. No form of information should be fed to it during the runs.<br />\r\n	4.&nbsp;The bot must not communicate with any wireless device during the runs.<br />\r\n	5.&nbsp;Lego kits are strictly prohibited, although readymade microcontroller boards and sensors are allowed.<br />\r\n	6.&nbsp;The bots must use on-board power supply. External power supply is not allowed.</p>\r\n<p>\r\n	<br />\r\n	<br />\r\n	&nbsp;<br />\r\n	<br />\r\n	<br />\r\n	&nbsp;<br />\r\n	<br />\r\n	&nbsp;</p>\r\n', 'citymaps', '4af9dd54-68fc-4cdf-b8da-1064bb1aea99', '<p class="info-box">\r\n	<span dir="ltr"><samp><span style="font-size: 12px;"><span style="font-weight: bold;">Round 1:<br />\r\n	</span></span></samp></span></p>\r\n<p class="info-box">\r\n	<span dir="ltr"><samp><span style="font-size: 12px;"><span style="font-weight: bold;"><span style="font-family: arial,helvetica,sans-serif;">1.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Each team will be given 1 run to complete the first round.<br />\r\n	2.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Skipping the bridge results in a penalty.<br />\r\n	3.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; There is penalty for not stopping at the penalty point.<br />\r\n	4.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; If the bot moves out of the track at any point of time during the run, it may be immediately placed again to its previous position on the track only once. On failing to follow the track after this, the team is eliminated.<br />\r\n	5.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Any damage to the arena will result in an immediate disqualification.</span></span></span></samp></span></p>\r\n<p class="info-box">\r\n	<span dir="ltr"><span style="font-size: 12px;"><span style="font-weight: bold;"><br />\r\n	</span></span></span></p>\r\n<p class="info-box">\r\n	<span style="font-size: 12px;"><span style="font-weight: bold;">Round 2:</span></span></p>\r\n<p>\r\n	<span style="font-size: 12px;"><span style="font-weight: bold;">1.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Each team has to deposit their bots before the arena is exposed to them. This is being done only to ensure that the last participant does not have the time advantage to modify the algorithm after the arena is exposed.<br />\r\n	2.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; This deposition of bots before the event begins has to happen at a certain specific deadline time that the final round participants will be made aware of well before the final round begins. Any changes that the teams need to make to their bots or their algorithms should be made before this. <br />\r\n	3.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; In cases of late deposition of the bots, the final call regarding the participation of this team will be at the discretion of the event managers.<br />\r\n	4.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Each team will be given a dry run in which the bot can completely traverse the arena. This run is only for exploring the arena for the positions of the penalty nodes and the bridges. This run is not considered for judging purposes.<br />\r\n	5.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; When the dry run ends, the bot should give an indication, preferably a blinking of LEDs. <br />\r\n	6.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; The dry run is immediately followed by the judging round. The bot will have to be placed back to the starting point, only after which, the judged run can begin. The bot should have a switch on-board to be pressed that starts this run.<br />\r\n	7.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Each team will be given 3 runs to complete this round. The best score amongst these will be considered for judging.<br />\r\n	8.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Again, on reaching the delivery point, the bot should stop for 5 seconds and also give an indication through LED blinking, only then, the forward run is considered as finished. <br />\r\n	9.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Just passing through the last node (delivery point) and giving an indication somewhere else will not be considered as a completed run.<br />\r\n	10.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Bridges can be used in both directions, both from start to delivery point and reverse.<br />\r\n	11.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; The bot that traverses from the starting point to the delivery point and back, in the minimum time (including the stopping time at the delivery point) wins.<br />\r\n	12.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Every passage of the bot over a penalty node results in penalty points (basically a time added to final score).<br />\r\n	13.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; If the bot moves out of a&nbsp; track at any point of time, no interruption by the participants will be allowed, but on moving out of the arena itself, that particular run will be ruled out and the only the remaining runs will be considered.<br />\r\n	14.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Any damage to the arena will result in an immediate disqualification.<br />\r\n	</span><br />\r\n	</span></p>\r\n<p>\r\n	<strong>Eligibility:<br />\r\n	</strong></p>\r\n<p>\r\n	<strong><br />\r\n	Round 1:<br />\r\n	</strong>Everyone with a valid college ID card is eligible to participate in the first round.<br />\r\n	<strong><br />\r\n	Round 2</strong>:<br />\r\n	The teams that clear the first round are eligible for the second round.&nbsp; <br />\r\n	&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>\r\n	<strong>NUMBER OF PARTICIPANTS PER TEAM:<br />\r\n	<span class="Apple-style-span" style="font-weight: normal;">Participants can form a team consisting of maximum 4 members.</span></strong></p>\r\n', '<!--[if gte mso 9]><xml>\r\n <o:OfficeDocumentSettings>\r\n  <o:RelyOnVML/>\r\n  <o:AllowPNG/>\r\n </o:OfficeDocumentSettings>\r\n</xml><![endif]--><!--[if gte mso 9]><xml>\r\n <w:WordDocument>\r\n  <w:View>Normal</w:View>\r\n  <w:Zoom>0</w:Zoom>\r\n  <w:TrackMoves/>\r\n  <w:TrackFormatting/>\r\n  <w:PunctuationKerning/>\r\n  <w:ValidateAgainstSchemas/>\r\n  <w:SaveIfXMLInvalid>false</w:SaveIfXMLInvalid>\r\n  <w:IgnoreMixedContent>false</w:IgnoreMixedContent>\r\n  <w:AlwaysShowPlaceholderText>false</w:AlwaysShowPlaceholderText>\r\n  <w:DoNotPromoteQF/>\r\n  <w:LidThemeOther>EN-US</w:LidThemeOther>\r\n  <w:LidThemeAsian>X-NONE</w:LidThemeAsian>\r\n  <w:LidThemeComplexScript>X-NONE</w:LidThemeComplexScript>\r\n  <w:Compatibility>\r\n   <w:BreakWrappedTables/>\r\n   <w:SnapToGridInCell/>\r\n   <w:WrapTextWithPunct/>\r\n   <w:UseAsianBreakRules/>\r\n   <w:DontGrowAutofit/>\r\n   <w:SplitPgBreakAndParaMark/>\r\n   <w:DontVertAlignCellWithSp/>\r\n   <w:DontBreakConstrainedForcedTables/>\r\n   <w:DontVertAlignInTxbx/>\r\n   <w:Word11KerningPairs/>\r\n   <w:CachedColBalance/>\r\n  </w:Compatibility>\r\n  <m:mathPr>\r\n   <m:mathFont m:val="Cambria Math"/>\r\n   <m:brkBin m:val="before"/>\r\n   <m:brkBinSub m:val="--"/>\r\n   <m:smallFrac m:val="off"/>\r\n   <m:dispDef/>\r\n   <m:lMargin m:val="0"/>\r\n   <m:rMargin m:val="0"/>\r\n   <m:defJc m:val="centerGroup"/>\r\n   <m:wrapIndent m:val="1440"/>\